item.title: Support Bracket for IKEA TROFAST
item.description:
If your bins are falling out of your IKEA TROFAST storage unit, these support brackets will help. The bins fit into slots cut into the unit, but if you load the bins up with anything heavy they tend to fall out. These supports add just a few extra millimetres of support on either side and that seems to be enough to correct the problem.

Shown are a picture of the slots before and after installation of the supports. I put two brackets in each slot: one near the front and one near the middle.

There is also a picture of the screws I used to install the brackets (I drilled first). The screws can be up to 5/8" in length. Screw head diameter can be up to 6.5mm (the brackets have countersunk holes so that the screw heads do not stick out).

item.title: Samsonite Wheel 61x18mm
item.description:
On my Samsonite rolling computer bag a wheel disintegrated when it was dropped (without the computer inside). Couldn't find a model here the right size so I designed my own. I decided to make it in 4 sections rather than 2 like most. This allows it to print flat with no support needed and allows the horizontal seams to be offset (see pictures).

Print 4 copies, use CA to glue 2 around the hub as straight as possible, glue the 3rd to them rotated ~90 degrees from the first 2, then glue the 4th to them all. If needed, fill any gaps with CA.

It's working well so far.

item.title: Lionel Gang Car brush plate
item.description:
Test fit, test fit, test fit... The arm should spin one direction nicely with no work. To get the thrust bearing in the plate you may need to spin a drill bit by hand in the hole. The arm should move up and down a little with the bearing installed at the right depth.
The brush holders should fit tight. You'll need to hone those holes a little. Maybe roll up sand paper and spin it in the hole, keep test fitting the holders.
I used PLA and have really only run it a minute at a time. The brushes might get hot enough to melt it, I haven't found out yet.

item.title: Kirby Portable Fume Extractor
item.description:
This fume extractor is remixed to add a cavity for a 18650 3.7V Li-Ion Cell and USB charging circuitry gutted from a portable charger. I put a switch between the 5V power and the 5V DC 80mm x 80mm fan from amazon. It also has a 4.7 x 4.7 x 0.3in Carbon Filter that I had to cut to fit in front of the 80mm fan.

It can be charged with a micro-usb cable just like any cheap portable low-amp USB charger from the convenience store (not a large powerbank).

I soldered the fan power (5 VDC) wire to the switch and then the switch to 5V pin on the USB connecter trace. There's enough space in the extractor TOP model for the wiring from the battery to the USB charging circuit and the wiring to/from the switch.

5V DC 80mm x 80mm fan:
https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B019ORFSD8/ref=ppx_yo_dt_b_search_asin_title?ie=UTF8&psc=1

item.title: Glowing Halloween Tombstone Keychain
item.description:
One idea that came to my head was a design related to the dead.

Only 45 minutes to make, it takes no longer than cookies to bake.

Familiar with the wear and tear of a key fob, I thought a 100% infill may do the job.

Drawn in Krita and made in Blender, then taken to Cura to render.

If you have read this far, I reward you a gold star.

If you have enjoyed this post in some way, throw a like my way.

If you have printed the file, then post your makes which I check for during my breaks.

Thank you for taking the time to read these silly rhymes.

Now I'm off to plan more designs.
